80+ excellent arrangement and development of material and argument, where the material has been handled with great dexterity. The work will be in excellent English and the presentation meticulous, with immaculate footnotes and extensive bibliography.
70+ careful thought has been given to the arrangement and development of material and argument.  The work will be in excellent English with appropriate footnotes and comprehensive bibliography.
60 - 69 adequate arrangement and development of material and argument.  The work will be in good English with appropriate footnotes and bibliography.
50 - 59 effort to organise the material and argument.  The work will be in adequate English with reasonable footnoting and a bibliography.
40 - 49 limited effort to organise the material and argument.  The work generally will be in satisfactory English but with limited footnoting and bibliography.
30 - 39 very little effort at organising the material.  The work will show significant errors in English and have poor footnoting and bibliography.
below 30 a lack of organisation of the material.  The work will show substantial errors in English and have very poor or a lack of footnoting and bibliography.

70+ wide reading and comprehensive knowledge.

50 - 59 fair range of reading and reasonable knowledge.
40 - 49 limited reading and incomplete knowledge.

70+ clear evidence of independent thought and the ability to defend a position logically and convincingly.
60 - 69 evidence of thought with a well-developed argument.
50 - 59 some evidence of thought with a serious attempt at an argument.
40 - 49 limited thought and argument.

50 - 59 some awareness of issues and their wider significance.

70+ Comprehensive awareness of socio-legal issues and a clear grasp of their wider significance. Balanced argument. Well argued.  Very good response to questions. Good critical analysis of issues. 
60 - 69 very good awareness of socio-legal issues and a serious understanding of their wider significance. Balanced argument with evidence of some critical discussion. Good response to questions. 
50 - 59 some awareness of issues and their wider significance. Clear argument. Limited critical discussion. Reasonable responses to questions. 
40 - 49 limited awareness of issues and their wider significance. Argument not always clearly advanced. No critical discussion. Lack of understanding of key concepts, principles etc. Some difficulty in answering questions/response to questions limited. 
Fail – very poor awareness of issues and of their wider significance, with incoherent argument and structure. Some major inaccuracies re- key principles etc. Unable to provide more than a very basic response to questions.

fields.lsp:
## Disability: Dyslexia

### Personal Details and Effects of Disability on Study

#### Reading
John has a slow reading speed, this is compounded by the need to re-read information. John struggles more when decoding and understanding technical terminology, so text which has a higher level of technical terminology will take John much longer to read through. John experiences visual disturbances unless reading from coloured backgrounds.  John finds that he learns better through visual and audio aids.

#### Written work
Grammar, spelling, the correct use of homophones and punctuation are all areas of difficulty for John. He also experiences challenges with getting ideas onto paper in a logical format. John may use words he can spell rather than those which are most appropriate; this may lead to his work not accurately demonstrating the true depth of knowledge held.

#### Proofreading
John does not always spot the errors in his own work.

#### Note-taking
John has a slow writing speed, this coupled with a difficultly with dividing the attention between listening, writing and reading means that John is not able to match the speed of delivery with his note taking speed.

#### Time Management and Organisation
John’s time management skills are weak and this coupled with the extra time his written work takes means that he may underestimate the time he will take to produce written work.

#### Communication
John feels nervous when reading aloud and may experience word finding difficulties.

#### Assessed work
Due to the difficulties outlined above John will require special arrangements for assessed work.

### Required Provisions

_Reading Text Books:_ Early notification of reading lists to give John time to do necessary reading for the course.

_Reading Handouts in Seminars:_ Provision of handouts before the seminar date via CLIC Learn would allow John to prepare properly.

_Note Taking:_ 
* Provision of the lecture notes / handouts prior to lecture before taught sessions to allow John to learn the information before the session.
* Permit John to take audio notes of all taught sessions.
* Tutors should look at the guidance on providing lecture notes and digital recordings through the following [link](http://www.canterbury.ac.uk/support/student-support-services/disability/information-for-staff.asp)
* Leave any additional notes displayed after the lecture to allow John time to copy them down

_Coursework:_ Implementation of special arrangements, please ensure that the feedback sheet clearly states that the Spelling, Grammar and Structure has been taken into consideration. Requests for extensions should be treated with sympathy.

_Examinations:_ Implement special arrangements for examinations. 25% extra time, use of a pc, consideration for spelling, grammar and structure of written work.

_Presentations_: Implement 25% extra time for presenting.

Content of Tutorial 
Student is finding it hard to adjust to the course.  Part of this seems to be unfamiliarity with systems such as CLIC- she says she finds these confusing.  Also having health problems, has been in hospital with a heart issue and has been off a few days.  Says that she feels she wants to drop the course.  Says it has not helped that she is told by tutors that the law programme is harder than other subjects.  

Tutor’s Comments 
Advised student she need to see KS if she wants to transfer onto a different programme.  However, spent some time reassuring her that a lot of students find the transition hard and a lot of these issues will be the same if she does another subject.  Told her to spend weekend thinking about things before making a decision.

Content of Tutorial 
EGB met with student for second meeting regarding the issues she has been having with the course.  She says she has spoken to family and decided she will carry on with course for time being.  Some issues with using CLIC.  She is not enrolled in all the modules.  This is because she has not yet been transferred from Law and CJS.  Advised she must contact KS about this.  

Tutor’s Comments 
Student to contact KS

Sakhile is studying Law & AC. She is originally from Zimbabwe and was living in Essex before moving to Folkestone with her job in the charitable sector. She left school in 2007 and came to the UK with her family who remain in Essex. She studied Law for a year at Anglia Ruskin but had to give up due to immigration problems. Those have now been resolved and she has leave to remain in the UK with the option to apply to remain indefinatley in 3 years time; she is not a Tier 4 student. She has to pay fees herself and must work to do so. She transferred with her job to Folkestone but lost it recently due to her change to student status; her employers were unable to continue to retain her as a part-time employee. Although she has paid her first term's fees and one month's rent in advance, the worry of not having a job has been stressful for her. Despite this she has been attending lectures and engaging with her modules. She does find the pre-reading quite demanding, but has bought text books. She siad that she needs to get a PC/laptop as she is finding it difficult commuting in when she needs to access a computer. She is however engaging with Clic using her mobile device. She seems committeed and eager to succeed, but will need monitoring given her current personal circumstances. I explained the pastoral care regime and suggested she contact me should she have any issues, particularly is personal circumstances change adversely. I confirmed that student health and wellbeing should be able to give her guidance on matters outside my domain.

Lauren informed me that she is settling in well and finds thinks ok. She had initially issues of doind online research but Ben's session has helped her out. She is confident in accessing meterials online. I assured her that I will be available for her in case she has any issues and adviced her to get in touch if she needs to. 

Gowri

Joesph did not turn up for the meeting schduled at 1.30pm.

Gowri

Has been having problems with childcare issues.  Having problems with student finance.  Cannot afford to buy books.  Having to rely on parents for finance.  Had a kidney infection, auntie passed away and then assumed it was reading week.  
Student loans have been delaying because of not having national insurance number and son's birth certificate.  Struggling financially.  
Advised to go and see student finance support to see if can apply for emergency funding.  
She will attend IDR next week but says she is very worried and panicked about the assignment which is a powerpoint presentation.  I will let BW know she will be attending and the reasons for failure to do so.  
EGB

Tutorial meeting.  Course is going well generally.  She said she is slightly worried about the amount of coursework but assured her that this is manageable.  She is having some issues with housemates but is making friends on the course.  
No concerns at this stage.

Nyasha is from Zimbabwe and has already finished another degree in Capetown before (Politics, IR and Gender Studies), She seems quite professional and hard working, and she profits a lot from her previous experiences. She has just joined a study group and is very enthusiastic about it. Doesn't seem to have any issues or problems, enjoys her experience so far and seems to be doing well.

Nyashsa aims to become a lawyer in Zimbabwe, probably specialising on disabled people's rights (one of her sisters has cerebral palsy).

Matt seems to be doing fine with his legal studies. He stated that he finds subjects interesting. He is part of a study group and he states that it helps him being on track with studies. 

Gowri

Amy seems to be settling in well. She sounded confident in her studies and she states that being in a study group is helping her. 

Gowri

Lauren is settling in well. She says that she is very good with time management and therefore is finding things are going well. 

Gowri

Being a mature student Simon informs me that he sometimes find himself falling behind compared to the younger students. I reassured him that he is doing fine in both of my modules and that he should not be discouraged at all. He sought for some assistance for the criminal law assessment essay question. I Provided him with some guidance. He seemed happy with it. He informs me that he is trying his best to balance out his studies and family life. 

Gowri

Sarah seemes to be settling in well. She said she is struggling with ELM at the moment and I encouraged her to meet up with Sharon and get some guidance from her. Other than that she said she is doing fine.

Gowri

James was originally down to study Primary Years Education but deferred his place and joined us this year to study Law & International Relations. He took a year out and taught in Zambia. His family background is Iranian and although his father is in the UK and James grew up and was educated here, most of his family remain in Iran some of whom, notably his Aunt, have been persecuted for their religious beliefs (his family are of the Bahá'í Faith) his Aunt has been arested and is imprisoned. This is one of the reasons for his choice of degree. James chose Canterbury to study as it is a similar city to the one in which  he grew up (St Albans). He really enjoyed his time there particularly school. He is living in St Georges and has good quality accommodation. I explained the pastoral care regime and he had nothing of real concern to raise with me except the fact that some of the seminar rooms are too small for the numbers of students. He is generally enjoying university life, his attendance is good, he is enthusiastic about his studies. He asked about work experience, particularly international law related, and I suggested that any kind of work expereinec would be an asset particularly in the area of the job market which he is aiming for. I also suggested that he might llike to speak to the volunteering service in the university to see what opportunities are available.

Louise is a mature student who has run her own business (beauty and hair salon in Herne Bay) for around 20 years already. She is also involved in a charity and has had some legal experience through that. Besides this, Louise was close to complete a business degree at the Open University, and says she might finish the remaining three modules when she finishes her law degree. She is also confident that she will be able to get a training contract, as she has friends in the legal profession.

Louise has missed a number of sessions at the beginning of the first term due to holidays that were apparently discussed and approved by Kasim prior to her beginning of studying.

Annabel seems to be getting along well overall, but claims to have had issues with the timetable. Therefore, she missed all sessions in ELIM so far. I have instructed her to make sure that she understands that figuring out her timetable is her responsibility. Annabel promised to catch up with ELIM now, will hopefully be in the seminar from next week on and will hopefully do her reading.

Dominic decided late to study law, was considering other options (business, politics, english literature). He enjoys reading a lot and seems quite happy with his late choice. Generally, he seems to be getting along very well, has great attendance so far and no problems to follow the classes. Dominic lives locally (6 miles away), and commutes by bus.
Did not show up for the meeting booked.

Joe is repeating the first year and had some issues as he needed to change the course (LS/AC -> Law with AC). Therefore, he wasn't aware of his timetable for his first weeks and has missed quite a few classes. He also has health issues (low level Tourette syndrome) that force him to stay at home from time to time, but he claims it is not much of a problem anymore. Student support is aware of his health issues.

Joe was (until this meeting) also not aware that he was supposed to be doing Contract Law this year. I will make sure he is on the CLIC board as soon as possible.

When asked about the reasons for repeating the last year, Joe is claiming similar issues (not being aware of all classes he was supposed to do), so we will need to watch out that Joe is aware of his responsibilities. He considers himself to be on top of the reading now, and believes that he will not have problems to pass this year. I have told him to make sure that he contacts the lecturer when he misses classes due to health reasons.

Joe is considering to become a solicitor later. His mother is involved in a medical negligence practice, and he is doing some work there.
Have contacted the student several times, but without any answers. Now I have arranged for a meeting with myself and Kasim to discuss how to proceed. The meeting is scheduled for 20 November.

Explained purpose of P/t system. Daudi is motivated and enjoys both law and international studies, already showing a good level of knowledge of international events. He is clear about wishing to work in the law, and we discussed the addition perhaps of some European languages to his skills set.
Zan could not make first meeting due to work duties abroad for CCCU. We will link in at some time later in November.

+ Explained the p/t system. 
+ Sarah is a part time mature student, who changed to 'Law with Criminology' from 'Sociology and Criminology'. She felt she had been treated rudely by sociology, had a meeting with Kasim and changed. As a consequence she did not properly start the programme until week 2 missing inductions. Her criminology classes begin next term, and at present she is doing ELILM and Criminal law. 
+ She does not yet really know any students on the course although she has spoken with two other p/t mature students, Zan and Julie Samaringhe. She feels that she has nothing in common with the younger students as she is a single mother with a child of 2 years. I asked her to try and get to know them without preconceptions. 
+ One problem has been that she has a child minder and arrives at classes as they start and leaves as they end - so there is no opportunities for social interaction. I have asked her to consider taking a day in Canterbury. Going to the library, studying there, having lunch there and getting to feel as if this is her university. Or to be on campus, she will inevitably see other students and familiarity will also lead to feeling part of something, at present she is very lonely. 
+ She also doubts that she is able to be successful on the course and this is panicking her somewhat. Sarah missed the library training on ELILM so I have contacted Karen Goodwin for a one to one with Sarah. 
+ We discussed her absences and I underlined the importance of seminar attendance. She came to my ELILM seminar for the first time on 6th November, this is in fact the 4th session. She has attended lectures.
+ At present she does not have a job. 
+ I will email her towards the end of term to see how she is getting on.

Jordan did not attend this meeting, and sent an email to state this on 3rd. I rearranged for 5pm on 12th November but he did not come. He sent an apology after missing the time stating he had thought my room was in Augustine house. However I asked him to attend after the lecture in Pg06 which he did not attend. I have rearranged 5pm 26th November after the lecture.

+ Explained the p/t system. 
+ Shada is studying Law with FI. 
+ In fact she does not think that she can succeed with law studies despite encouragement from other students on the course. 
+ She had wanted to do single honours FI but there was a problem with her access course evidence. She cannot find it and Shauna specifically wants information about the detail of that access to match it to the entry for FI. Shauna was getting her mother to search for it. 
+ I told her it was her responsibility to ring her old college for a transcript and get it to Shauna asap. 
+ She is adamant she wants to transfer to single honours FI. 
+ But I warned her it was very late in the term to effect such a change.

Explained the purpose of the p/t system. 
He appears settled and relaxed although he says he has not yet been sent a copy of his LSP on clic learn as he was led to believe. 
He has now sent me the email from student support attaching his plan as we do not yet have one on our database. 
He has a job and all seems fine. But I think that he may have concerns that he has not referred to and I will liaise with him again at the end of term.

+ Explained the purpose of the p/t system. 
+ He appears to be happy, says that he has friends on the course and his attendance is excellent. 
+ He does have financial concerns. His maintenance grant paid for his accommodation up until December 6th. He has been in contact with student support and has just filled out forms for a grant. But he has been told this will take around three weeks to 'process'.
+ He has been unable to buy all of the books required as set texts, and is very low on funds for other things, currently with £100 for the next three weeks. 
+ He is 17 and has been living alone estranged from his parents since Feb 2013. He likes where he lives and likes his landlady who allows him to keep his motor bike in her shed. 
+ Because of his age it is difficult to get work, and he only has a job doing a paper round at present. As he lives in Margate this means he is late for 9am lectures and there are three of these in his schedule. 
+ I will link in with him in 3 weeks time to see how all is going.

Explained the purpose of the p/t system. 
She is happy and settling well. 
We discussed her absence from seminars.

She is organised and highly motivated to complete the degree well. She is trying to do assessments early but I suggested that whilst she may wish to do this, she should not submit until the relevant classes and she has had time to go back to her work in light of additional information given in relevant lectures/seminars.
She has 50% allowance for lectures and seminars. So she only has to make up the work for 50% of the time she is in classes. 
I raised study leave, she did not think she was entitled to any, I asked her to look at the personal development allowances for her in her department. She is willing to take holiday leave if she has to.

Explained the p/t system. He is a Japanese Tier 4 student, and his prior study was in Switzerland. He lives with a host family in the UK and he is very happy with the family. He finds Canterbury culturally different to what he expected, and food is a bit of an issue as it is so difference, but  he has no problems.

Sara is repeating the year having failed 5/6 modules last year. She mainatins that she is confident that things will improve this year (I'm not so sure). I tried to get her to explain what went wrong last year, but she just wouldn't open up, save for saying that last year was challenging. Her attendance was not great and this year she assures me that it will improve. She did however explain that she found seminar groups difficult and doesn't really like them; she finds it difficult to contribute. She seems very shy. She was wearing a brace on her wrist having being dignosed with writst stress and inflammation. I explained the importnatnce of her bringing any difficulties to my attention so that appropriate support could be provided.

Repeat student. Has a medical condition. This prevented him from engaging. He had a LSP in place last year but not in place this year as condition has improved. His attendance has been very much better this year, although he did have some time off recently due to concussion following a minor RTA.  He doesn’t feel he needs extra support. I suggested that he let me know if he does feel he needs support and I could bring his needs to the attention of Student Health & Wellbeing. He wants to be a solicitor and has given his CV to about 7 firms in Sittingbourne. I suggested he get some work experience and also mentioned the uni’s volunteering service.

Getting on OK so far; no issues to report. From North London (Boreham Wood). Didn’t study Law at 6th form college but did do it at GCSE. Took a gap year and went travelling. Hasn’t really got much idea about the what she wants to do in terms of career at present so is keeping her options open. She does have a contact in the legal profession who does family law. She wants to try to get some work experience and has had some in the past. Samantha seems to be settling in fine.

Michael atended the Simon Langton Grammar School in Canterbury before taking a foundation degree at Staffs Uni. He didn't want to continue as the social life at Staffs was not good. He finds the Law degree programme more challenging; finding the resources, reading requirements etc. He favours a legal career at present as he has an inetrest in advocacy  and suggested that he think about joining the student law society. He will be looking into gaining some work exprieince during his holiday periods so as to enhance his cv.
Called Ashleigh to confirm the meeting tomorrow. On the phone, Ashleigh informed me that she is planning to withdraw from the course, but she is willing to meet us tomorrow to find out her options.

Sara attended a meeting with Kasim and me. She is not attending lectures/seminars and has a real problem with seminars. She couldn't at first explain why but did say later that she found it difficult tot say anything in seminars and gets very nervous.

She is living in St Martin's Terrace with other students; one of them, Joanne Elston-Evans is a third year Law student. Shehas made some friends on the Law degree and doesn't seem to have any issues with her social life. 

With Sara's agreement a referal was made to SH&W reporting to them the following; Sara has been seen by both her personal tutor and the PD for Law regarding concerns firstly about her attendance and secondly about her fear of seminars; when she does attend she does not contribute. She is a Year 1 repeat student having failed badly last year. She says that she left things very much to the last minute last year and is not good at exams. There may be an underlying reason for her extreme shyness and fear of contributing in seminars that SH&W may be able to establish. She promises to attend seminars and we agreed with Sara that tutors would discuss with her specific questions that she could work on which she could then try to answer in class so as to build up her confidence. She is taking advantage of the peer mentoring sceme within the dept. and we wonder of there are any other study strategies that may be put in place to lend support to this so as to improve Sara's confidence generally.

Sara promised to attend seminars and would talk to us if she had any issues/difficulties inthe meantime we would make the referral and aslo inform GN and EG-B about the seminar strategy to implement

Met Ashleigh together with Kasim Sheikh to talk about her options. Ashleigh has very serious personal and family issues that have kept her from studying and that make it obvious that she will not be able to complete the year. Kasim has suggested either withdrawing or interrupting, depending on the outcome of Ashleigh's own discussion with Student Finance England. 

Later in the week, Ashleigh informed us that she would like to interrupt and start over next September, potentially in a part-time degree.

EGB met with student brielfy after seminar.  Explained that it is very important for her to attend regularly.  She has missed scheduled tutorial meetings without explanation.  Student assured me that she would be attending regularly from now on.  Said she had had a few personal problems which were now resolved.

Met with students regarding performance issues.  Student explained she had been having some family problem but thatthings were now resolved.  She assured me that she always does the reading even if she misses seminars.  I explained to her that it is very important to attend all classes and she assured me that she would in the future.  (EGB)

fields.headline: Welcome to the CCCU Law Database
fields.text:
Hello everyone,

Good luck setting up your modules and filling them with students. Don't forget to change your password (under "My Account" in the top right corner).

Please let me know if you have any problems.

Tobi

fields.headline: Changes
fields.text: Thanks to Ellen's suggestion, I have added a "remove student from module" button. If you added a student accidentally to your module, you can now click the "X" on the right side next to the student's name in the module overview.

fields.headline: Changes
fields.text: Thanks to Sharon's feedback, I have now revised the form to add or edit modules. Now there are buttons that insert sensible defaults for the teaching weeks in the attendance part. You can, of course, still change what these buttons suggest. I hope this helps!

fields.headline: Marksheet template for "Legal Problem" added
fields.text: When adding or editing a module (the little "Edit" button in the blue box of the module overview), you can now also select "No marksheet required" (for example for multiple choice tests) and "Legal Problem". The pencil symbol will only appear for assessments that require a marksheet, the other marks can be edited over the Marks button in the module view.

fields.headline: And another marksheet template
fields.text:
I have now also added the template for the oral presentation, which you can select when you edit your module. The only one missing is the group presentation template, which will probably cause me some headaches...

And I got rid of an annoying bug - thanks to Gowri for pointing it out!

fields.headline: Warning sign in module view
fields.text: When you entered your first two weeks of attendance, you will see a warning sign next to the students that did not attend twice. Clicking the sign will open a "send email" dialogue.

fields.headline: Bug fixed
fields.text: The warning signs for missing attendance should now appear, even if you only had 2 sessions so far.

fields.headline: Some additions
fields.text: I have now added some more small things: you can now identify part time students directly in the lists, and I have added the only LSP we have so far for year 1. You should be able to see a warning triangle for that in the overview of your module.

fields.headline: Email functionality
fields.text:
I have added email functions to the Module pages (the one where you can assign seminar groups etc). This way you won't have to look through cryptic CLIC menus to find out how to email everyone in your module, and you won't have to email everyone if only need to notify one seminar group of something. Try it out and let me know if it works for you!

Besides that, I have (hopefully) fixed some issues that Ben had thanks to the ancient Internet Explorer version installed on our office computers. Now it should be possible to do changes to students in the student overview (Students - Year x), even if you are using Internet Explorer 9.

fields.headline: Tutor functions
fields.text:
Thanks to a comment by Ben, I have added an "Email all Tutees" button as well, and I have added another function that might be useful to the Tutee list (under Students-My Tutees): a warning sign next to students that might require attention (currently it warns about having missed the last 2 sessions in a module, about failed modules and about failed assessments in a foundational module).

Hope this helps!

fields.headline: Small Change
fields.text: I have just added a small change: now only the modules with data entered are visible in the Student / Tutee view. This way you can focus on the modules that matter rather than seeing three modules with "Attendance 0/None" in your overview.

fields.headline: Phone numbers
fields.text: The phone numbers for most students are now on the database as well. You can find them on the student's page - either by clicking on their name in the module or year view, or by searching for a part of their name (first or last name) in the search box above. If there are problems with the numbers, feel free to update them by clicking on "Edit".

fields.headline: Changes to the student view
fields.text:
After receiving some feedback from Ben and Louise, I have made some radical changes to the students' individual pages:

+ The pages are now much less cluttered and prettier
+ This has made some space for extra information like the students' addresses
+ I have ended the somewhat artificial separation between student and tutee view. This means that, as a student's tutor, you can now see (and add) meeting information regardless of how you got onto his or her page. Whether you use the search function or click the name from anywhere inside the database, you will see the same information.
+ To address some confidentiality issues that Ben was raising, I have now made sure that only the personal tutor of a student can see the meeting record. If there is something everyone should know about a student (eg "Attendance in the first term was affected by a severe illness, should be better now"), please write that in the "Notes" section.
+ As our "Head of Pastoral Care", Ben can see all meeting records on the system.
+ As before, if a student gets a new tutor, the new tutor will be able to see the meeting records from before, but will not be able to edit / delete them.
+ I have added some addresses that Louise gave me. Unfortunately, address information from QL are very, very messy, and attempting to import them opened a whole new world of pain for me, but I believe I managed.

Let me know if you like the changes and if there is anything else you would like me to address!

fields.headline: Marking
fields.text:
On Ben's request, I have now added an export function for the marksheets, which will simply give you a nice PDF with all marksheets you created, alphabetically sorted. You can then upload this to the shared drive, print it for the students, add it to your records or do whatever you want with it.

Simply click on "Export" in your module view. If you already created marksheets, the options will show up there.
